**Project: Self-hosted LLM inference on Clore.AI GPU marketplace**

## Platform: Clore.AI

Clore.AI is a P2P GPU rental marketplace. You rent Docker containers on other people's GPUs. You don't control the host OS — only what runs inside the container.

**How Clore's boot process works:**
- You specify a Docker image and a "startup script" when creating an order
- Clore's SSH Autoinstall replaces the container entrypoint with S6 overlay (a process supervisor) that runs SSH + `/root/onstart.sh`
- **Startup script** = runs ONCE on first container creation. Used for installing software and downloading models
- **`/root/onstart.sh`** = runs EVERY time the container starts/restarts. This is where the llama-server command lives
- After writing onstart.sh, call `s6-svc -r /var/run/s6/services/onstart` to trigger it. If S6 is ready it runs immediately; if not, S6 runs it when it finishes deploying

**Clore gotchas we discovered the hard way:**
- The startup script runs in a minimal shell with a stripped PATH. Tools installed via `apt install` during the script often can't be found by name immediately — the shell doesn't see them. This is why we moved to building a custom Docker image with tools pre-baked
- `huggingface-cli` is deprecated; the new command is `hf`
- `hf download --local-dir` doesn't reliably place files where expected on these containers
- Model downloads can produce 0-byte files silently — always verify filesize before proceeding
- SSH can take several minutes to become available even after Clore says "deployed"
- Images that force a non-root default user don't work with SSH Autoinstall

## Hardware

Currently renting 2x RTX A5000 (23 GB VRAM each, 46 GB total). Previously tested single RTX 3090/4090 (24GB). On Clore spot pricing, RTX 3090 runs $0.03-0.12/hr, on-demand ~$0.20/hr per GPU.

**RTX A5000 vs RTX 3090:** Same Ampere architecture (compute capability 8.6), but A5000 has 768 GB/s memory bandwidth vs 3090's 936 GB/s. Expect ~18% lower tok/s vs 3090 figures.

## Model: Qwen3.6-35B-A3B

Mixture-of-Experts. 35B total parameters, only 3B active per token (256 experts, 8 activated + 1 shared). Practically this means:
- VRAM: needs space for all 35B params (like any 35B model)
- Compute per token: like a 3B model, so very fast (~100-135 tok/s on single 3090)
- Using Unsloth `UD-Q4_K_XL` GGUF quantization — 20.81 GiB on disk (reported as 22.1GB elsewhere)
- **Architecture is hybrid Transformer-Mamba** (not pure transformer): only ~4 out of 40 layers use full attention with KV cache; the rest use SSM (Mamba). This means the KV cache is tiny — only ~3.5 KB per token at q8_0 vs ~80 KB for a pure-transformer model of the same size. A 262K context window requires only ~931 MiB for KV.

## Docker image

Base image: `ghcr.io/ggml-org/llama.cpp:server-cuda`

Custom Dockerfile to pre-bake dependencies (avoids PATH issues in startup script):

```dockerfile
FROM ghcr.io/ggml-org/llama.cpp:server-cuda
RUN apt update -y && DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive apt install -y wget curl aria2 python3 python3-pip && pip install huggingface_hub[hf_transfer] --break-system-packages && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
ENV HF_HUB_ENABLE_HF_TRANSFER=1
RUN mkdir -p /models
```

Push to Docker Hub, use as the Clore container image.

## Working startup scripts

**Single GPU (3090/4090, 24 GB) — file: `startup.sh`**

Uses `-c 98304` (96K context), all layers on one GPU.

**Dual GPU (2x A5000 or 2x 3090, 46–48 GB) — file: `startup2gpu`**

```bash
#!/bin/sh
mkdir -p /models
MODEL="/models/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf"
URL="https://huggingface.co/unsloth/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-GGUF/resolve/main/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf"
export HF_TOKEN="hf_your_token_here"

if [ ! -f "$MODEL" ]; then
    echo "[$(date)] Starting model download..." >> /var/log/startup.log

    echo "[$(date)] Trying aria2c..." >> /var/log/startup.log
    aria2c -x 16 -s 16 -k 1M -d /models -o Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf \
        --header="Authorization: Bearer $HF_TOKEN" \
        "$URL" >> /var/log/startup.log 2>&1

    if [ ! -f "$MODEL" ]; then
        echo "[$(date)] aria2c failed, trying wget..." >> /var/log/startup.log
        wget --header="Authorization: Bearer $HF_TOKEN" \
            -O "$MODEL" "$URL" >> /var/log/startup.log 2>&1
    fi

    if [ ! -f "$MODEL" ]; then
        echo "[$(date)] wget failed, trying curl..." >> /var/log/startup.log
        curl -L -H "Authorization: Bearer $HF_TOKEN" \
            -o "$MODEL" "$URL" >> /var/log/startup.log 2>&1
    fi
fi

FILESIZE=$(stat -c%s "$MODEL" 2>/dev/null || echo 0)
if [ "$FILESIZE" -lt 1000000000 ]; then
    echo "[$(date)] ERROR: All download methods failed ($FILESIZE bytes)" >> /var/log/startup.log
    rm -f "$MODEL"
    exit 1
fi

echo "[$(date)] Download complete ($FILESIZE bytes)" >> /var/log/startup.log

cat > /root/onstart.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/sh
export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/app:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH
/app/llama-server \
  -m /models/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf \
  --host 0.0.0.0 \
  --port 8080 \
  -ngl 999 \
  -fa on \
  -c 262144 \
  -np 1 \
  --cache-type-k q8_0 \
  --cache-type-v q8_0 \
  --no-mmap \
  --jinja \
  -b 4096 >> /var/log/llama-server.log 2>&1
EOF

chmod +x /root/onstart.sh
s6-svc -r /var/run/s6/services/onstart
```

## llama-server flags and why each matters

- **`-ngl 999`** — offload all layers to GPU
- **`-fa on`** — flash attention. Must be `-fa on` not just `-fa` on newer llama.cpp builds (we hit this error)
- **`-c 262144`** — full 262K context (model's training max). On 2x A5000, KV cache costs only ~931 MiB due to hybrid Mamba architecture, leaving 16+ GB headroom
- **`-c 98304`** — 96K context for single GPU (3090/4090). Uses 23.1GB of 24.5GB VRAM with 1.4GB headroom
- **`-np 1`** — single parallel slot. llama.cpp auto-sets `np=4` which allocates 4x KV slots and adds overhead even for a single user. Explicitly setting `np=1` gave a 35% speed increase (40 → 54 tok/s) on 2x A5000
- **`-b 4096`** — batch size for prompt processing (prefill). Default is 2048. Setting 4096 gives ~336 tok/s prefill vs slower default. Does not affect decode speed
- **`--cache-type-k q8_0 --cache-type-v q8_0`** — the key optimization. Halves KV cache VRAM with no measurable quality loss on Qwen3.6. This is how we went from 8K to 98K context on the same GPU
- **`--no-mmap`** — loads weights fully into VRAM instead of memory-mapping from disk. Better for GPU-only inference
- **`--jinja`** — enables Jinja chat templates, required for Qwen3.6's chat format

## What we confirmed works

- Q4_K_XL at 98K context on single 3090: stable, 1.4GB headroom, server reports healthy
- Q4_K_XL at 262K context on 2x RTX A5000: stable, 16.5GB total VRAM headroom, 54–68 tok/s decode, 336 tok/s prefill
- q8_0 KV cache quantization: no quality loss, halves KV cache footprint
- aria2c with 16 parallel connections: ~52 MB/s download speed on Clore nodes
- Three-tier download fallback (aria2c → wget → curl): handles whatever tools are available
- HuggingFace token passed via Authorization header to all download methods
- `-np 1` is critical for single-user deployments — auto `np=4` was causing 35% speed penalty

## What we confirmed does NOT work or help

- **Speculative decoding on this model:** extensively benchmarked, every configuration (ngram-cache, ngram-mod, classic draft with Qwen3.5-0.8B) is 3-12% slower on 3090. The MoE architecture causes expert thrashing during draft verification
- **Ollama:** wraps llama.cpp but hides KV cache quantization, flash attention, and batch size controls. llama-server directly gives ~1.4x speed and 2x context
- **`hf download`/`huggingface-cli`:** unreliable on Clore containers. Downloads to cache instead of target dir, or doesn't find the binary
- **`-fa` without `on`:** newer llama.cpp builds require `-fa on`, bare `-fa` throws an error
- **Tensor split mode (`-sm tensor`) for multi-GPU:** not implemented for MoE architectures including Qwen3.6
- **Single GPU at 262K context:** technically loads (22,555 MiB / 23,028 MiB on A5000) but only leaves 184 MiB free, cramping the compute buffer. Resulted in 23 tok/s — slower than dual GPU. Use single GPU only for ≤96K context
- **Auto `np=4` on dual GPU:** llama.cpp default. Wastes KV slots and adds overhead for single-user setups. Always set `-np 1` explicitly

## 2x RTX A5000 — confirmed working configuration

**VRAM layout (idle, after model load):**
- GPU0: 15,557 MiB used / 23,028 MiB total → 7,172 MiB free
- GPU1: 13,330 MiB used / 23,028 MiB total → 9,400 MiB free
- Total free: ~16.5 GB

**Performance:**
- Decode: 54–68 tok/s (short sequences; higher end with warm GPU)
- Prefill: ~336 tok/s
- Context: 262,144 tokens (full model maximum)

**Why dual GPU pipeline is not 2x faster:** pipeline parallelism is sequential — GPU0 runs its layers, then GPU1 runs its layers per token. No parallel speedup for single-token decode. The second GPU exists purely for VRAM capacity to hold the full 262K KV cache.

**Why speed improved over default (40 → 54 tok/s):** `-np 1` eliminates the 4-slot KV pool and its management overhead that llama.cpp auto-allocated when `n_parallel` was not set.

